The dataset that I have chosen to do my research over is the sample data that was provided on country economy/social status. When looking over this dataset I have developed 3 research questions that I will be focusing on throughout this report. Does the continent a country is on limit or expand their trade oppurtunities? What countries have the furthest to go to becoming developed? What are the biggest problems that developing countries are facing in becoming developed? With these three questions in mind I have cleaned the dataset to only have the variables that I need for my analysis by removing the variables X.1 and X.

data <- read.csv("sample-data.csv")

The side-by-side bar chart below depicts the average Percent of Annual GDP for Exports and Imports by Continent (2002-2016). This specifically means that I found the average value of imports and exports relative to Annual GDP for a country from a given continent where I included all observations of countries that ranged between 2002 and 2016 in the calculations to find the average values for a country from a given continent. From the side-by-side bar chart below it does seem to some extent that the continent a country is a part of can limit or expand their trade opportunities. Specifically countries in Asia seem to benefit the most from trading, as on average countries in Asia have the highest annual export and import value relative to their annual GDP when compared to the annual export and import values relative to the annual GDP of the average country in other continents. Specifically countries in both Oceania and South America seem to benefit the least from trading, as on average countries in these two continents have the lowest annual export and import values relative to their annual GDP’s when compared to the annual export and import values relative to the annual GDP of the average country in other continents.

## Create a new dataset with a variable that is the average Exports...GDP for every continent and a variable that is the average Imports...GDP for every continent

The histogram below depicts the average HDI between 2002 and 2016 of all countries in the data set. This histogram of average HDI is multimodal and left skewed, meaning that a majority of countries have high HDI’s. There does not seem to be any noticable outliers in the histogram that are separated from the rest of the data. From the histogram below it seems that some of the countries that have the furthest to go in becoming developed have an HDI of less than 0.5. The list of these countries include Haiti, Ivory Coast, Madagascar, Malawi, Senegal, Tanzania, and Uganda.

The parallel coordinate plot below depicts the average standardized and centered values of Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Debt, Debt.Per.Capita, Deficit…M…, Expenditure.M…, Expenditure.Per.Capita, Corruption.Index, Exports, Exports…GDP, Imports, Imports…GDP, Population, Fertilility.Rate, Crude.death.rate, HDI, Life.expectancy, and CO2.Tons.per.capita of countries between the years of 2002 and 2016. This parallel coordinate plot is also grouped by the status variable which will be able to illustrate the difference between developed and developing countries in the dataset. When looking at the parralel coordinate plot it seems that some of the biggest problems for developing countries in becoming developed is GDP.per.capita, corruption.Index, Crude.death.rate, HDI, and Life.expectancy. I believe that these variables that I have listed are specifically some of the biggest problems for developing countries because there seems to be complete seperation between the groups of developing and developed countries in these variables and that also this seperation in the values of these variables seems to be very large. I did not list variables like Debt.Per Capita and CO2.Tons.per.capita even though both variables seemed to create complete seperation between the groups of developing and developed countries and also this seperation between the groups seemed to be very large, because neither of these variables would qualify as problems for developing countries as they would not want to get into more debt or have a higher CO2.Tons.per.capita.

To further look into what countries have the furthest to go in becoming developed I decided to use clustering on only the countries that are listed as “developing”. I performed hierarchical clustering using Bray’s distance and Ward’s method as for the reason of not wanting clusters that included only 1 or 2 observations. When looking at the Within/Between Ratio vs. Number of Clusters Plot I found that 2 clusters makes the Within/Between Ratio the highest. I also found that 2 clusters makes the ch index the lowest in the ch index vs. Number of Clusters plot, so the number of clusters that I chose was 2. I then used multidimensional scaling to plot these clusters and found that 3-dimensions is enough to provide good enough representation of the data as the cumulative proportion of the distance captured in 3-dimensions is approximately 0.83. After plotting the 3 dimensional data I was able to see that my clusters did a good job of separating the data into multiple large clusters and not just one cluster that had almost all the observations in it, even with some of the large outliers that I was seeing in the plots of coordinate 3 vs. 1, and the plot of coordinate 3 vs. 2. To see which one of these two clusters of countries was further away from developing I looked to see which cluster had worse average values of the variables I identified as being some of the biggest problems for developing countries using the parallel coordinate plot above. From doing this I found that the cluster that had the furthest to go in becoming developed was cluster 2 as countries in cluster 2 on average had a much worse GDP.per.capita of $4372.735 , Corruption.Index of 32.48376, Crude.death.rate of 0.007688752, HDI of 0.6330291, and Life.expectancy of 67.80159. The average values of cluster 1 tended to be much better in these variables as the average country in cluster 1 had a GDP.per capita of 15700.193, a Corruption.index of 48.96667, a Crude.death.rate of 0.006585741, a HDI of 0.7382519, and a Life.expectancy of 73.82367. From the clustering analysis I can conclude that the countries of Angola, Argentina, Boliva, Brazil, Cameroon, Chile, China, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, Egypt, Ghana, Guatemala, Haiti, India, Indonesia, Ivory Coast, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Malaysia, Medxico, Morocoo, Pakistan, Peru, Phillippines, romania, Senegal, South Africa, South Korea, Sri Lanka, tanzania, Thailand, Tunisia, Turkey, Uganda, Venezuela, Vietnam, and Zambia that are in cluster 2 have the furthest to go in becoming developed. The countries in cluster 1 that are still not developed but are closer to becoming developed than countries in cluster 2 include Albania, Botswana, Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras, Hong Kong, Israel, Jamaica, Jordan, Luxembourg, Mauritius, Namibia, Nicragua, Panama, Paraguay, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, and Uruguay.

## Average values for all countries except continent and data variables
averagecountryvalues <- joinedparcoord

##Take all developed countries out of the data
averagecountryvalues <- averagecountryvalues %>% dplyr::filter(status == "Developing")
##Calculate the distance between the average values of countries
Dist <- vegdist(averagecountryvalues[, c(-1, -2)])
## Warning in vegdist(averagecountryvalues[, c(-1, -2)]): results may be
## meaningless because data have negative entries in method "bray"
HClust <- hclust(Dist, method = "ward.D2")

## Within/between ratios
WithinBetween <- sapply(2:10, function(x){
  cluster.stats(Dist, clustering = cutree(HClust, x))$wb.ratio
})

qplot(2:10, WithinBetween, geom = c("point", "line"), xlab = "Number of Clusters", ylab = "Within/Between Ratio", main = "Bray's Distance(Ward's Method)")

## Ch Index
ChIndex <- sapply(2:10, function(x) {
  cluster.stats(Dist, clustering = cutree(HClust, x))$ch
})

qplot(2:10, ChIndex, geom = c("point", "line"), xlab = "Number of Clusters", ylab = "ch Index", main = "Bray's Distance (Ward's Method)")

## Choose Hierachical Clustering with Bray's Distance and wards Method and 2 clusters because the within/between ratio is the highest for 2 cluster and the Ch index is the lowest for 2 clusters

To further investigate what are the biggest problems developing countries are facing in becoming developed I decided to use logistic regression with a response variable of status to find which variables effect status of a country the most. Specifically I performed logistic regression on data where a single observation is from a country in a given year that could be between the years of 2002-2016. First, I split my data into a training and test set using the function CreateDataPartition, specifically to keep the proportion of status = “developed” the same between the test set and the training set. My training set contained 70 percent of the observations from the full data set and my test set contained 30 percent of the observations from the full data set. After my data was split into a training and test set I fit a logistic regression model on my training set with the response variable being status and the explanatory variables being all other variables from the sample data file except for Country and Date. I then performed Backward Selection using AIC on the full model I just fit and found that optimal variables chosen by Backward Selection were Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Debt.Per.Capita, Imports, CO2.Tons.per.capita, and Continent. I then fit a logistic regression model on my training dataset with the response variable being status and the explanatory variables being GDP.per.capita(I didn’t use annual.GDP because of high correlation with GDP.per.capita), Debt.Per.Capita, Imports, CO2.tons.per.capita, and Continent. After fitting this logistic regression model using the variables found from Backward selection I then found the predicted classes of the status variable on the test set using this logistic regression model. From these predictions I found that the misclassification rate of the logistic regression model found using Backward Selection was 0.01630435. The confusion matrix below between the actual values from the test set and the predicted values using the logistic regression model with backward selection shows that the model misclassified 3 out of 112 actual “Developed” countries and also misclassified 3 out of 256 actual “Developing” Countries. I then decided to fit a random forest with status as my response variable and every variable in the data set except for Country and Date as my explanatory variables on my training set. I set the number of trees to 1500 and the nodesize to 5, meaning that a terminal node could not have less than 5 observations. I then used this randomForest to predict status on my test set and found that the misclassifcation Error Rate was 0. This means that my random forest that I fit on the training set with all the predictors in the dataset except for country and Date did not misclassify one single observation in the test set. From using the importance plot below and the meanDecreaseGini as this random forest is used for classificatio, you can see that the variables that were most important in the random forest model to predicting status were Expenditure.Per.Capita, Continent, Debt.Per.Capita, HDI, and GDP.Per.Capita. When comparing the performance of the logistic regression model found using backward selection and the random forest on the test set, the random forest performs better as it has a misclassification error rate of 0 and the logistic regression model has a misclassification error rate of 0.01630435. This could be due to a multitude of factors one of which could be that actual decision boundary is irregular and non linear so the random forest as a non-parametric model will perform better. From these two different classification techniques the variables that I found are most important to classifying the status of a country are Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Debt.Per.Capita, Imports, CO2.Tons.per.capita,Continent, HDI, and Expenditure.per.capita. From these variables only Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Imports, Expenditure.Per.Capita, and HDI are actually problems that these developing countries are facing and variables that they need to see a drastic increase in.

##Set seed so we get the same random sample every time
set.seed(1)
dim(data)
## [1] 1230   22
##Use Create Data Partition to create training and test set that have the close to the same proportion of status = "Developing" 70 percent of the data is also going in the training set
trainindex <- createDataPartition(data$status, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)

##Use backward selection to fit a logistic regression model
LogRegFull <- glm(data = data[trainindex, ], status ~. - Country -Date, family = "binomial")
## Warning: glm.fit: algorithm did not converge
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
LogRegBackwardSelection <- step(LogRegFull, direction = "backward")

I conducted a one-way Manova test with 6 populations which are the continents in the dataset (Africa, Asia, Europe, North America, Oceania, South America), where the invidividual observations in this dataset are countries in a given year between 2002-2016. The mean vectors that are being evaluated in this one-way Manova include the variables Exports, Exports…GDP, Imports, and Imports…GDP. The null hypothesis for this test is that the population means for Exports, Exports…GDP, Imports, and Imports…GDP are equal between Continents. The alternative hypothesis is that at least two continents (populations) will have at least one different population mean value out of the variables Exports, Exports…GDP, Imports, and Imports…GDP. The Wilk’s test static calculated in this one-way Manova was 0.6387582 which converts to an F statistic of 29.30656 with the degrees of freedom (20, 4050.549). The p-value for this one-way Manova is < 2.22e-16 which is less than 0.05, so we can reject the null hypothesis. This means that at least two continents will have at least one different population mean value out of the variables Exports, Exports…GDP, Imports, and Imports…GDP. From this conclusion we have gotten from the one-way Manova test we can say that the continent a country is on does limit or expand their trade oppurtunities.

##Create a dataframe with only the variables that involve trading
trade <- data %>% dplyr::select(Exports, Exports...GDP, Imports, Imports...GDP, Continent)

##Each observation from this data frame is a specific country at a specific year


lm <- lm(cbind(Exports, Exports...GDP, Imports, Imports...GDP) ~ Continent , data = trade)
manova <- Manova(lm)
summary(manova)

I conducted a Hotelling’s two sample T2-Test to confirm that there is actually a significant difference between the two clusters of developing countries that I created above, cluster 1 which are the countries that are closer to becoming developed and cluster 2 countries which are further away from becoming developed. I conducted this Hotelling’s two sample T2-test on a data set where single observations represent the average values for a country for the years between 2002-2016. To make our observations using this test more interpretable I will only be evaluating the clusters using the variables Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Imports, Expenditure.Per.Capita, and HDI, which I identified as the biggest problems facing developing countries. The null hypothesis for this test is that the population mean values of Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Imports, Expenditure.Per.Capita, and HDI are the same for Cluster 1 and Cluster 2. The alternative hypothesis for this test is that at least one population mean value of Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Imports, Expenditure.Per.Capita, and HDI are different for Cluster 1 and Cluster 2. The T2 statistic is 34.41645, and the F-statistic is 6.3827 with the degrees of freedom (5, 51). The p-value is equal to 0.0001127 which is less than 0.05, so we can reject the null hypothesis. This means that we can conclude from the test that at least one population mean value of Annual.GDP, GDP.per.capita, Imports, Expenditure,Per.Capita, and HDI are different for Cluster 1 and Cluster 2.

Cluster1 <- averagecountryvalues[averagecountryvalues$Cluster == 1, c(3, 4, 14, 10, 19)]
Cluster2 <- averagecountryvalues[averagecountryvalues$Cluster == 2, c(3, 4, 14, 10, 19)]
n1 <- nrow(Cluster1)
n2 <- nrow(Cluster2)
p <- ncol(Cluster1)
t2test <- HotellingsT2Test(Cluster1, Cluster2)
t2test
## 
##  Hotelling's two sample T2-test
## 
## data:  Cluster1 and Cluster2
## T.2 = 6.3827, df1 = 5, df2 = 51, p-value = 0.0001127
## alternative hypothesis: true location difference is not equal to c(0,0,0,0,0)
## Find the T2 Statistic
t2test$statistic *p *(n1 + n2 - 2) /(n1 + n2 - p -1)
##          [,1]
## [1,] 34.41645
